{
  "$schema": "../../schema/pathway.schema.json",
  "id": "catecholamine-metabolism",
  "name": "Catecholamine biosynthesis and degradation",
  "category": "neurotransmitter-metabolism",
  "summary": "The tyrosine-derived catecholamines dopamine, noradrenaline and adrenaline are built by four sequential enzymes and cleared by the parallel action of monoamine oxidase and catechol-O-methyltransferase into the diagnostic end-metabolites homovanillate (HVA), vanillylmandelate (VMA), MHPG and the metanephrines.",
  "description": "This module covers the complete tyrosine → catecholamine axis and its catabolism. **Biosynthesis (4 steps):** tyrosine hydroxylase (TH) hydroxylates L-tyrosine to L-DOPA using tetrahydrobiopterin (BH4), Fe2+ and O2 — the rate-limiting, committed step and the principal site of control. Aromatic L-amino-acid decarboxylase (AADC/DDC), a PLP enzyme, decarboxylates L-DOPA to dopamine. In noradrenergic and adrenergic cells dopamine is taken up into secretory vesicles where dopamine β-hydroxylase (DBH), a copper enzyme that consumes ascorbate, β-hydroxylates it to noradrenaline; in adrenal-medullary chromaffin cells phenylethanolamine N-methyltransferase (PNMT) then transfers a methyl group from S-adenosylmethionine (SAM) to give adrenaline. **Regulation:** the catecholamine end-products feedback-inhibit TH by competing with BH4, while PKA (and CaMKII/PKC/ERK) phosphorylate TH at Ser40/Ser19 to relieve that inhibition — coupling firing rate and cAMP to synthesis. Adrenal glucocorticoids induce PNMT (and TH) transcription, making adrenaline output cortisol-dependent. **Degradation:** the catecholamines and their O-methylated derivatives are oxidatively deaminated by monoamine oxidase A/B (MAO, on the outer mitochondrial membrane) to reactive aldehydes (DOPAL, DOPEGAL and their methoxy analogues) plus H2O2, and independently O-methylated by COMT (SAM-dependent, SAH-inhibited). Aldehyde dehydrogenase (ALDH2) oxidizes the aldehydes to acids and aldehyde/aldose reductase (AKR1A1/AKR1B1) reduces them to glycols. The branches converge on the clinically measured end-products: **HVA** (dopamine), **VMA** and **MHPG** (noradrenaline/adrenaline) and the **metanephrines** (fractionated normetanephrine/metanephrine, the sensitive markers of pheochromocytoma). Loss of nigral dopamine underlies Parkinson's disease; MAO-B and COMT inhibitors are used to spare dopamine, and the DOPAL aldehyde is implicated in dopaminergic neurotoxicity.",
  "organisms": ["human"],
  "tissues": ["adrenal-medulla", "sympathetic-neuron", "brain", "chromaffin-cell", "locus-coeruleus", "substantia-nigra"],
